ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the formation of radical species inside a MB filled with an inert gas, we used a periodic simulation box containing 64 water molecules under vacuum atmosphere as model system (Fig. 2
                        ). Since it has been reported that extreme conditions of temperature, on the order of thousands of Kelvin, and surrounding pressure, on the order of hundreds of atmospheres, are developed in the vapor phase inside cavitation bubbles before their transient collapse [68], several simulations under a fixed pressure of 600 atm and temperatures ranging from 1000 to 6000 K were performed. All simulations were run for about 10 ps. Within this time scale, no radical formation was revealed at temperatures below 6000 K; however, in the simulation carried out at 6000 K, the homolytic rupture of one of the OH bonds in water was observed after a few ps. It appears that, only at this temperature or higher, the thermal energy accumulated along this bond is high enough to cause H2O dissociation through the following unimolecular process:

                              H2O → HO + H
